  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Deborah Weston accounces that Wendell Phillips is to be here. Deborah is worried about Anne W. Weston&apos;s health. Deborah has 25 scholars. She describes the conspicuous politeness of a Mrs. Chase, whose young son had written her enthusiastically about the anti-slavery fair (in Boston). She remarks on the state of abolitionists here: &quot;I have no pleasure in any of these brethren...I don&apos;t fellowship anything here.&quot; On Tuesday, Jan. 24, Deborah writes about Wendell Phillips&apos;s visit. &quot;His lecture before the Lyceum this evening was considered very fine, slightly whiggy &amp; rather conservative.&quot; In a conversation about &quot;The Slave,&quot; Wendell Phillips said &quot;that it was said at one time that [Richard] Hildreth wrote it.&quot; [The &quot;Slave&quot; referred to is the book, The Slave; or Memoirs of Archy Moore, by Richard Hildreth, published anonymously in 1836; a later edition was entitled only Memoirs of Archy Moore.] Deborah Weston said, &quot;I like Wendell [Phillips]. I think Ann Terry has done very well.&quot; [Ann Terry was Ann Terry Greene, who married Wendell Phillips in 1837.]</subfield>
